To answer this question, I would need the actual stock return data to perform the Fourier transform and analyze the frequency components. However, I can provide you with the Matlab code to perform the Fourier transform and find the frequency components with amplitudes greater than 0.2. Once you have the stock return data, you can use this code to find the answer.

```matlab
% Assuming the stock return data is stored in a variable called 'stock_returns'
n = length(stock_returns);
Fs = 1; % Sampling frequency (1 day)

% Calculate the Fourier transform
Y = fft(stock_returns);

% Calculate the two-sided spectrum
P2 = abs(Y/n);

% Calculate the single-sided spectrum
P1 = P2(1:n/2+1);
P1(2:end-1) = 2*P1(2:end-1);

% Calculate the frequency vector
f = Fs*(0:(n/2))/n;

% Find the frequency components with amplitudes greater than 0.2
threshold = 0.2;
index = find(P1 > threshold);

% Display the number of frequency components with amplitudes greater than 0.2
num_freq_components = length(index);
disp(['Number of frequency components with amplitudes greater than 0.2: ', num2str(num_freq_components)]);
```

Replace the 'stock_returns' variable with your actual stock return data, and run the code in Matlab. The output will display the number of frequency components with amplitudes greater than 0.2.
